digester
Class Rule

java.lang.Object
  digester.Rule

public class Rule
extends java.lang.Object

Rule does the heavy lift for the Validation Components. This is where the code is written for each of the rules encountered in the XML configuration file.

You can use this javadoc to see a listing of available rules by ignoring the getter and setter methods below and using the method name as the rule "type" in the XML configuration file. Examples of use, as they appear in the XML configuration file are given below.

BoundingBox

public void BoundingBox()
                 throws java.lang.Exception
Check that coordinates are inside a bounding box. The bounding box declaration uses well-known text.

Example:

<rule type="BoundingBox" name="Moorea" decimalLatitude="DecimalLatitude" decimalLongitude="DecimalLongitude" level="warning"> <field>BOX3D(-18.5 -150.8,-16.7 -148.4)</field> </rule>

Throws:
java.lang.Exception

checkInXMLFields

public void checkInXMLFields()
                      throws java.lang.Exception
checkInXMLFields specifies lookup list values. There are two ways of referring to lookup, lists:

1. Listing values in XML fields, like:

<rule type="checkInXMLFields" name="PreparationType" level="warning"> <field>card_mount</field> <field>envelope</field> <field>fluid</field> <field>pin</field> <field>riker_mount</field> <field>slide</field> <field>resin_mount</field> <field>pin_genitalia_vial</field> <field>other</field> </rule>

2. Refering to values in a lookup list in the configuration file list element, like:

<rule type="checkInXMLFields" name="relaxant" level="warning" list="list3"/>

Throws:
java.lang.Exception

checkTissueColumns

public void checkTissueColumns()
                        throws java.lang.Exception
Check that well number and plate name are entered together and correctly. Takes a tissue and plate column specificaiton and sees that well numbers are formatted well and with range.

Example:

<rule type="checkTissueColumns" name="" plateName="format_name96" wellNumber="well_number96" level="warning"/>

isNumber

public void isNumber()
              throws java.lang.Exception
checks for valid numbers. This uses absolute value function in SQLLite and recognizes the following as non-numeric values ("abc","15a","z159") However, the following are recognized as numeric values ("15%", "100$", "1.02E10")

RequiredColumns

public void RequiredColumns()
RequiredColumns looks for required columns in spreadsheet by looking for them in the tags

Example:

<rule type="RequiredColumns" name="RequiredColumns" level="error"> <field>Coll_EventID_collector</field> <field>EnteredBy</field> <field>Specimen_Num_Collector</field> <field>HoldingInstitution</field> <field>Phylum</field> </rule>

uniqueValue

public void uniqueValue()
                 throws java.lang.Exception
Check a particular column to see if all the values are unique. This rule is strongly encouraged for at least one column in the spreadsheet NOTE: that NULL values are not counted in this rule, so this rule, by itself does not enforce a primary key... it must be combined with a rule requiring some column value

Example:

<rule type='uniqueValue' column='materialSampleID' level='error'></rule>

Throws:
java.lang.Exception

validateNumeric

public void validateNumeric()
                     throws java.lang.Exception
Checks for valid numeric values, looking in the value attribute field for ranges. Multiple ranges can be specified in value, like: value:">=-90 and <=90" or, simply value:">=0"

Throws:
java.lang.Exception
